<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 1 — PHILOSOPHY
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s1">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-tag">01 · Core Principle</div>
    <h2>This Plan Is About <em>Both</em></h2>
    <p>What we're actually optimizing for — and why it changes everything</p>
  </div>

  <div class="philosophy">
    <div class="philosophy-tag">The Foundational Shift</div>
    <p>The best financial plan is not the one that maximizes your portfolio at retirement. It's the one that <strong>maximizes your life</strong> across the entire arc — including the years you're 26 and traveling, 34 and exhausted with toddlers, 44 and at the peak of your career, and 60 and walking out the door together. You don't get those decades back.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>The previous plan optimized for maximum wealth. This one optimizes for a great life at every age, with enough wealth at the end to be genuinely free. The difference isn't recklessness — it's rebalancing. You'll still max your Roth IRAs every year. You'll still get the full employer match on both 401(k)s. You'll still invest substantial amounts. But you'll also take two real trips per year, go out on a Friday night without guilt, have the kids in whatever activities they love, and upgrade your home when it makes sense for your family — not just your spreadsheet.</p>
    <p>By living a fuller life along the way, you'll likely be <strong>better partners, better parents, and more fulfilled at work</strong> — which often accelerates career growth anyway. This is a more complete theory of wealth.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout sage">
    <div class="callout-lbl">What Changes vs. the Previous Plan</div>
    <p><strong>Lower savings rate (25–30% vs. 45–55%).</strong> Higher lifestyle spending. Generous travel budget at every phase. Kids born before she turns 30 (earlier timeline). Both retire at 60 (not him at 50, her at 60). Target ~$3.5M in real dollars at retirement — enough for a secure, comfortable $120K+ annual income at a healthy 3.5% withdrawal rate. Not $10 million. Not barely enough. <em>Just right.</em></p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 2 — EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s2">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-tag">02 · Executive Summary</div>
    <h2>The <em>Numbers</em> Still Work Beautifully</h2>
    <p>Lower savings rate, better life — and still a secure, comfortable retirement</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout sage">
    <div class="callout-lbl">✓ Verdict: Absolutely Achievable — With Room to Breathe</div>
    <p>On dual incomes that grow from $164K to $335K+, saving 25–30% of gross income while spending generously on life, you reach approximately <strong>$3.2–3.8M in real (inflation-adjusted) dollars</strong> at age 60. At a 3.5% withdrawal rate, that's $112K–$133K/year in spending power — for two people with no mortgage (home paid off or nearly so), children grown, and Medicare at 65. You will not worry about money in retirement. You will also not have worried about money during your working years. That's the win.</p>
  </div>

