<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 4 — LIFE CHAPTERS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s4">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-tag">04 · The Journey</div>
    <h2>Your Life in <em>Five Chapters</em></h2>
    <p>A financial and personal roadmap for each distinct era — savings and experiences in balance</p>
  </div>

  <div class="chapters">
    <div class="chapter">
      <div class="ch-age">
        <div class="ch-age-num">23</div>
        <div class="ch-age-to">–24</div>
        <div class="ch-age-lbl">2026–27</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ch-body">
        <div class="ch-years">Chapter 1 — Foundation & Courtship Years</div>
        <h3>Build the base. Enjoy being young. Don't live like you're already retired.</h3>
        <p>You're 23 with a good job, no rent, and your whole future ahead of you. This is the chapter for establishing habits — Roth IRA on autopilot, 401(k) contribution going in on Day 1, a small emergency fund. But it's also the chapter for exploring your city, traveling with your soon-to-be-dual-income future, and not treating every dollar as sacred. She finishes her degree; she starts her career. Life is genuinely exciting right now.</p>
        <div class="ch-priorities">
          <div class="ch-pri">Max Roth IRA immediately ($7K/yr) — the one rule that never bends <span class="ch-tag ct-save">Always</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">10–12% to 401(k) — capture the employer match above all else</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Save $18–22K cash for first car purchase in 2027 <span class="ch-tag ct-save">Goal</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Pay minimums on student loans — 5% loans lose to the stock market over time</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">$500–700/month for fun, dates, a few weekend trips <span class="ch-tag ct-fun">Live It</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="chapter">
      <div class="ch-age">
        <div class="ch-age-num">24</div>
        <div class="ch-age-to">–28</div>
        <div class="ch-age-lbl">2027–31</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ch-body">
        <div class="ch-years">Chapter 2 — Dual Income, DINKs, & Real Adventures</div>
        <h3>The best financial chapter of your lives. Spend some of it.</h3>
        <p>She starts working mid-2027. Your household income jumps to $164K overnight and climbs toward $200K+. Student loans retire by 2029. Before kids arrive (she's targeting her first at age 27), you have roughly 2–3 years as a dual-income, no-kids couple with relatively low fixed expenses. This window is finite. It's also the window for real travel — Europe, Japan, national parks, road trips. You will not have this flexibility again until your 40s.</p>
        <div class="ch-priorities">
          <div class="ch-pri">Both max Roth IRAs ($14K combined) — still the bedrock <span class="ch-tag ct-save">Always</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Increase 401(k)s to 15–18% of gross each; shift to Traditional as income rises</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Aggressively pay off $40K student loans by end of 2029 ($1,200+ extra/month)</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Save for House #1 down payment (target: 20% on $520–560K by 2030)</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">$1,200–1,800/month for a real life: dining, concerts, weekend escapes, one big trip per year <span class="ch-tag ct-fun">Earn It</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Taxable brokerage starts after loans paid: $1,000/month minimum <span class="ch-tag ct-save">Bridge Fund</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="chapter">
      <div class="ch-age">
        <div class="ch-age-num">27</div>
        <div class="ch-age-to">–35</div>
        <div class="ch-age-lbl">2030–38</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ch-body">
        <div class="ch-years">Chapter 3 — Family Years (Joyful, Constrained, Worth Every Penny)</div>
        <h3>Two kids. Daycare. Love and chaos. Still investing. Still living.</h3>
        <p>Kid 1 arrives when she's 27 (his age 28). Kid 2 when she's 29 (his age 30). She takes a 6-month leave each time and returns full-time. Daycare peaks around $2,500/month in the years they overlap. Combined income is $240K–$280K by this point — daycare is real money, but it's manageable. You keep investing steadily, you keep taking at least one family trip per year, and you don't treat parenthood as a financial emergency. By age 35, both kids are in public school and the cash flow opens dramatically.</p>
        <div class="ch-priorities">
          <div class="ch-pri">Roth IRAs: never stop, no matter how hard the daycare years feel <span class="ch-tag ct-save">Sacred</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Both 401(k)s: at minimum enough to capture full employer match; ideally 15%+ each</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Open 529 plans when each child is born ($150/month per child) <span class="ch-tag ct-save">529s</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">House #1 purchase at age 28–29 (mortgage on $520–560K; 20% down)</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Keep a $1,000–1,500/month fun/travel budget even during the squeeze years <span class="ch-tag ct-fun">Non-Negotiable</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Dependent Care FSA ($5K/yr) to offset daycare costs pre-tax — easy win</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="chapter">
      <div class="ch-age">
        <div class="ch-age-num">35</div>
        <div class="ch-age-to">–52</div>
        <div class="ch-age-lbl">2038–55</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ch-body">
        <div class="ch-years">Chapter 4 — The Acceleration Years (Both Kids in School, Income at Peak)</div>
        <h3>Cash flow opens. Invest hard. Travel better. This is your prime.</h3>
        <p>Daycare ends. Kids are in public school. Combined income climbs toward $300K+. This is when the real wealth-building happens — and also when you have the freedom to travel more ambitiously, upgrade your home, and spend on the experiences that define a well-lived life. The portfolio compound rate accelerates. By your mid-40s, you'll have a portfolio north of $1.5M and growing by more in annual returns than you contribute. Let it work.</p>
        <div class="ch-priorities">
          <div class="ch-pri">Max all tax-advantaged space: both 401(k)s ($47K+ total) + both IRAs ($14K) = $61K+ <span class="ch-tag ct-save">Maximize</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Taxable brokerage: $2,000–3,000+/month on top of 401(k)s</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Travel budget rises to $18K+/year — this is when you do the big trips <span class="ch-tag ct-fun">Live Fully</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Consider House #2 upgrade at age 38–42 when kids are in school and cash flow permits</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">529s funded to target — stop contributions when each hits $50K</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Age 48–50: begin gradually building a bond tent; start Roth conversion planning</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="chapter" style="border-bottom:none">
      <div class="ch-age">
        <div class="ch-age-num">52</div>
        <div class="ch-age-to">–60</div>
        <div class="ch-age-lbl">2055–63</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ch-body">
        <div class="ch-years">Chapter 5 — Final Stretch: Eyes on the Horizon</div>
        <h3>Finish line in sight. Protect the portfolio. Plan the exit.</h3>
        <p>Eight years to go. Portfolio is ~$2.5M+ and growing. Children are adults. Combined income likely $340K+. This is the chapter for de-risking, Roth conversions, and fine-tuning your retirement income plan. It's also the chapter for your best travel — bucket list items, anniversary trips, the experiences that require your best health and energy. You're almost there. Keep investing. Don't stop living. Walk out the door together at 60.</p>
        <div class="ch-priorities">
          <div class="ch-pri">Continue maxing all accounts; build 2-year cash buffer starting at age 57 <span class="ch-tag ct-save">Safety</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Roth conversion ladder: convert $50–70K/year from Traditional 401(k) while still in moderate tax brackets</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Shift allocation: 80/20 by 55, 70/30 by 58, 65/35 by 60</div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Age 59: price ACA marketplace for the 60–65 bridge; budget $25K/year <span class="ch-tag ct-life">Plan Ahead</span></div>
          <div class="ch-pri">Do the big bucket-list travel in your late 50s — health and energy are assets <span class="ch-tag ct-fun">The Good Stuff</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

