<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 6 — TRAVEL & FUN
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s6">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-tag">06 · The Point of All This</div>
    <h2>Travel, Experiences & <em>Actually Living</em></h2>
    <p>Explicit travel budgets by life phase — not aspirational, actually planned for</p>
  </div>

  <div class="philosophy" style="padding:34px 44px">
    <div class="philosophy-tag">Why This Section Exists</div>
    <p>Most financial plans treat travel and experiences as a <strong>variable to cut</strong> when times are tight. This one treats them as <strong>non-negotiable line items</strong> — because the research is unambiguous that experiences (not things) produce lasting happiness, and because you are 23. You will never again have the health, energy, and freedom of your 20s, 30s, and 40s. Plan to use them.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="travel-grid">
    <div class="travel-card">
      <div class="travel-icon">✈️</div>
      <div class="travel-phase">Phase 1 · Ages 23–24</div>
      <div class="travel-budget">$4,800</div>
      <div class="travel-per">per year</div>
      <div class="travel-desc">One real road trip or domestic trip. Weekend escapes. Don't be broke but don't be boring.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="travel-card">
      <div class="travel-icon">🌍</div>
      <div class="travel-phase">DINK Years · Ages 25–27</div>
      <div class="travel-budget">$10,800</div>
      <div class="travel-per">per year</div>
      <div class="travel-desc">This window doesn't last. One big international trip. One domestic long weekend. Go.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="travel-card">
      <div class="travel-icon">👨‍👩‍👦</div>
      <div class="travel-phase">Family Years · Ages 27–35</div>
      <div class="travel-budget">$7,200</div>
      <div class="travel-per">per year</div>
      <div class="travel-desc">Family beach week. National parks. Kids remember experiences more than things.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="travel-card">
      <div class="travel-icon">🗺️</div>
      <div class="travel-phase">Acceleration · Ages 35–50</div>
      <div class="travel-budget">$15,000</div>
      <div class="travel-per">per year</div>
      <div class="travel-desc">This is the era. International trips. Anniversary travel. Bucket list begins in earnest.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="travel-card">
      <div class="travel-icon">🏔️</div>
      <div class="travel-phase">Final Stretch · Ages 50–60</div>
      <div class="travel-budget">$18,000</div>
      <div class="travel-per">per year</div>
      <div class="travel-desc">Bucket list. Peak health, peak income, near-peak freedom. Do the big ones now.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="travel-card">
      <div class="travel-icon">🌅</div>
      <div class="travel-phase">Retirement · Ages 60+</div>
      <div class="travel-budget">$15,000+</div>
      <div class="travel-per">per year (from portfolio)</div>
      <div class="travel-desc">Fully funded from portfolio. $122K/yr retirement income has room for everything you want.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout sage">
    <div class="callout-lbl">What This Costs the Portfolio</div>
    <p>The difference between spending $10,000/year more on travel vs. investing it for 37 years at 7% is approximately <strong>$167,000</strong> in final portfolio value per extra $10K annual spend. That sounds like a lot until you realize it's 5% of a $3.5M portfolio. You are trading 5% of your final portfolio value for 37 years of experiences. The economics of a well-lived life look very different when you actually model them.</p>
  </div>
</section>

