      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 class="sub">Withdrawal Access Ladder</h3>

  <div class="ladder-step">
    <div class="ls-age">57–59<span>Pre-retire prep</span></div>
    <div class="ls-body">
      <span class="ls-tag lst-a">Preparation</span>
      <h4>Build the 2-Year Cash Buffer + Begin Roth Conversions</h4>
      <p>Three years before retirement, move 2 years of expenses ($190–200K) into a high-yield savings account or short-term treasuries. This is your sequence-of-returns buffer. Simultaneously, begin converting Traditional 401(k) → Roth IRA at $50–70K/year while still in moderate tax brackets (income is dropping as you prepare mentally for exit).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ladder-step">
    <div class="ls-age">60<span>Day One</span></div>
    <div class="ls-body">
      <span class="ls-tag lst-a">Taxable First</span>
      <h4>Draw from Taxable Brokerage — No Restrictions, LTCG Rates</h4>
      <p>Your taxable brokerage account has no age restriction. Withdraw here first. Long-term capital gains tax at your income level will be 0–15% — far below what you paid contributing. This is your primary income source from age 60–65. Also eligible: Roth IRA <em>contributions</em> (not earnings) — always accessible, always penalty-free.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ladder-step">
    <div class="ls-age">60–65<span>Healthcare bridge</span></div>
    <div class="ls-body">
      <span class="ls-tag lst-t">Healthcare</span>
      <h4>ACA Marketplace — Manage MAGI for Subsidies</h4>
      <p>The most expensive healthcare window: ages 60–65 before Medicare. Budget $22,000–30,000/year for a couple on ACA marketplace. By drawing primarily from taxable brokerage (low/zero income) and Roth contributions (not counted as income), you may qualify for meaningful ACA subsidies — potentially reducing actual premiums to $12,000–18,000/year. Plan for the worst; budget $25K/year to be safe.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ladder-step">
    <div class="ls-age">59½<span>Full unlock</span></div>
    <div class="ls-body">
      <span class="ls-tag lst-r">All Access</span>
      <h4>Full Access to All Accounts — Traditional IRA/401(k) Without Penalty</h4>
      <p>Six months into retirement, all Traditional accounts become fully accessible without the 10% penalty. Roth earnings also fully unlocked (account is well past 5 years old). This is largely a non-event in your plan since you have the taxable bridge, but it means your full $3.5M is now completely liquid and accessible.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ladder-step">
    <div class="ls-age">65<span>Medicare</span></div>
    <div class="ls-body">
      <span class="ls-tag lst-t">Healthcare Relief</span>
      <h4>Medicare — Healthcare Costs Drop 60–70%</h4>
      <p>Medicare Part A (free), Part B (~$185/month each), Part D (~$50/month each), and a Medigap supplement (~$200/month each) = roughly $900/month total for both. Compared to $2,000–2,500/month ACA marketplace. This frees $1,100–1,600/month in spending — effectively a raise in retirement. Portfolio should still be near full strength at this point (~$3.2–3.4M).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ladder-step" style="border-bottom:none">
    <div class="ls-age">67<span>Social Security</span></div>
    <div class="ls-body">
      <span class="ls-tag lst-r">Bonus Income</span>
      <h4>Social Security — The Plan Didn't Need It, But You Earned It</h4>
      <p>At 40+ years of contributions in cleared/hospital positions, your combined Social Security at full retirement age (67) could be $35,000–55,000/year combined. This plan projects zero Social Security to be conservative. In reality, it likely replaces a large portion of your portfolio withdrawals — potentially allowing the portfolio to keep growing well into your 70s, or enabling significantly more spending/giving. Treat it as a bonus.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout sage">
    <div class="callout-lbl">Healthcare Is the Only Real Risk at 60</div>
    <p>With a $3.5M portfolio and $95K annual spending, market risk is negligible at a 2.7% SWR. The one variable that genuinely requires planning is healthcare from ages 60–65. Budget $25,000/year for ACA coverage, aggressively manage your MAGI via Roth draws (not counted as income) to qualify for subsidies, and confirm this number at age 58 when you can get real quotes. Once Medicare starts at 65, this risk essentially disappears.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 12 — RISKS & OPTIMIZATION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s12">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-tag">12 · Risk & Optimization</div>
    <h2>What Could Go Wrong — And <em>How to Win More</em></h2>
  </div>

  <div class="risk-grid">
    <div class="risk-card">
      <div class="risk-hdr"><span class="risk-icon">💸</span><span class="risk-title">Lifestyle Creep Past the Fun Budget</span><span class="rbadge rb-hi">High Risk</span></div>
      <p>This plan explicitly allocates more for lifestyle than typical FIRE plans — which is good. The risk is "spending $1,800/month on fun" becoming $3,200/month without anyone noticing over 5 years. Review your fun budget annually; adjust intentionally, not accidentally. The line between "living well" and "leaking savings" is behavioral, not mathematical.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="risk-card">
      <div class="risk-hdr"><span class="risk-icon">🏥</span><span class="risk-title">ACA Healthcare Bridge (60–65)</span><span class="rbadge rb-hi">High Risk</span></div>
      <p>Pre-Medicare coverage is your single biggest retirement planning risk. Budget $25K/year worst case. Manage MAGI via Roth draws. Get quotes at 58. If ACA costs run $30K+/year, the portfolio still handles it comfortably at 3.5% SWR — but you'll want the explicit plan in place, not the hope it works out.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="risk-card">
      <div class="risk-hdr"><span class="risk-icon">🔒</span><span class="risk-title">Clearance Continuity</span><span class="rbadge rb-md">Medium Risk</span></div>
      <p>TS/SCI clearance is worth $15–30K/year in salary premium. Losing it mid-career would require a recalibration. Maintain impeccable financial hygiene (no unexplained debt, no foreign financial entanglements) and personal conduct. Your clearance is as valuable as a professional license — protect it accordingly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="risk-card">
      <div class="risk-hdr"><span class="risk-icon">🏗️</span><span class="risk-title">Two House Purchases + Daycare Overlap</span><span class="rbadge rb-md">Medium Risk</span></div>
      <p>House #1 purchase at ~age 28 overlaps with the start of Kid 1's daycare. Don't stretch on House #1 pricing just because dual income arrived — maintain a 15% gross income mortgage payment ceiling. If House #2 is purchased in your late 30s, wait until daycare is fully cleared (age 35+) to avoid compressing investments during the most powerful compounding decade.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="risk-card">
      <div class="risk-hdr"><span class="risk-icon">📊</span><span class="risk-title">Under-Saving in the Early Years</span><span class="rbadge rb-md">Medium Risk</span></div>
      <p>The "more lifestyle" approach only works if the non-negotiable savings (Roth IRA, at-minimum 401(k) match) actually happen every year. Missing even 3 years of Roth IRA contributions in your 20s costs roughly $60–80K in retirement wealth (time in market). Automate everything. The discipline is in the setup, not the willpower.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="risk-card">
      <div class="risk-hdr"><span class="risk-icon">📉</span><span class="risk-title">Market Sequence at Retirement</span><span class="rbadge rb-lo">Low Risk</span></div>
      <p>At 2.7–3.5% SWR on $3.5M, a 2-year bond tent plus the cash buffer you build at age 57–59 makes sequence of returns risk minimal. Even a 40% market crash on Day 1 of retirement leaves you with $2.1M at a temporary 4.8% SWR — still well within safe territory historically. This risk is real but manageable with the bond tent strategy.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 class="sub">Highest-Leverage Optimizations</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <thead><tr><th>Opportunity</th><th>Effort</th><th>Lifetime Impact</th><th>When</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Max Roth IRA both accounts — every single year</td><td class="g">None (auto-debit)</td><td class="sd">~$180–250K at retirement from these contributions alone</td><td>Now, forever</td></tr>
      <tr><td>HSA if employer HDHP available</td><td class="g">Very low</td><td class="sd">$7,300/yr triple tax-free; invest all of it; ~$180K if started at 25</td><td>Immediately</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dependent Care FSA during daycare years</td><td class="g">Very low</td><td class="sd">$5K/yr pre-tax × 6 years = ~$10,500 in tax savings</td><td>2031–2037</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Virginia Invest529 tax deduction</td><td class="g">None (in the plan)</td><td class="sd">~$7,800 total VA tax savings across both children</td><td>2032+</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Her hospital pension verification</td><td class="g">Low (just ask HR)</td><td class="sd">If available, a defined benefit pension could add $1,500–3,000/month at 60 — potentially transformative</td><td>This week</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Negotiate clearance premium at every job change</td><td>Medium (requires research)</td><td class="sd">Each $10K salary increase = ~$180K additional portfolio at retirement</td><td>Every transition</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Backdoor Roth when income exceeds IRA limits</td><td>Medium (annual process)</td><td class="sd">Never lose the $7K Roth contribution; at $240K+ combined income, do the backdoor</td><td>When applicable</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Roth conversions at ages 55–65</td><td>Medium (annual planning)</td><td class="sd">Convert $50–70K/yr at lower tax rate; save estimated $40–90K lifetime taxes vs. traditional withdrawals</td><td>Age 55–65</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ACA subsidy management at 60–65</td><td>Medium (tax planning)</td><td class="sd">Keep MAGI below ~$90K MFJ for premium tax credits; draw from Roth (not income) to hit this</td><td>Age 60–65</td></tr>
